# Adding Records

Use prepared statements for INSERT as well.

```php
$sql = "INSERT INTO users (name, email, age) VALUES (:name, :email, :age)";
$stmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);
$stmt->execute([
    'name' => 'John Doe',
    'email' => 'john@example.com',
    'age' => 30
]);

echo "Inserted ID: " . $pdo->lastInsertId();
```

`lastInsertId()` returns the auto-generated ID of the last insert.

```php
<?php
$name = 'Jane';
$email = 'jane@example.com';
$age = 25;

$sql = "INSERT INTO users (name, email, age) VALUES (:name, :email, :age)";
$stmt = $pdo->prepare($sql);
if ($stmt->execute(['name' => $name, 'email' => $email, 'age' => $age])) {
    echo "User added with ID: " . $pdo->lastInsertId();
} else {
    echo "Insert failed.";
}
?>
```

# Modifying and Removing

Same pattern: prepare and execute.

```php
// UPDATE
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("UPDATE users SET email = :email WHERE id = :id");
$stmt->execute(['email' => 'newemail@example.com', 'id' => 5]);

// DELETE
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("DELETE FROM users WHERE id = :id");
$stmt->execute(['id' => 5]);
```

You can get the number of affected rows with `$stmt->rowCount()`.

```php
<?php
$id = 10;
$newAge = 32;

$stmt = $pdo->prepare("UPDATE users SET age = :age WHERE id = :id");
$stmt->execute(['age' => $newAge, 'id' => $id]);

$count = $stmt->rowCount();
echo "Updated $count rows.";
?>
```
